<Layout title="Zero-Shot Prompting">
    <div class="container">
        <h1>‚ö° Zero-Shot Prompting</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">
            Ask the AI to do something it was never explicitly trained to do ‚Äî
            and it just works. Here's why, when, and when it doesn't.
        </p>
        <div class="doc-link">
            <a
                href="https://www.promptingguide.ai/techniques/zeroshot"
                target="_blank">üìÑ View Original Docs ‚Äî promptingguide.ai</a
            >
        </div>

        <!-- Core concept -->
        <div class="section-title">üí° What Is Zero-Shot Prompting?</div>
        <div class="core-card">
            <h3>No examples. No training. Just ask ‚Äî and it works.</h3>
            <p>
                Zero-shot means you give the AI a task <strong
                    style="color:#e2e8f0;">with zero examples</strong
                >. You don't show it "here's what a correct answer looks like."
                You just ask, and it answers ‚Äî because it already knows enough
                from being trained on massive amounts of text.
            </p>
            <div class="analogy">
                üß† <strong>Analogy:</strong> Imagine hiring someone who has read every
                book ever written. You say "classify this review as positive or negative"
                ‚Äî they just do it, without needing you to show examples first. That's
                zero-shot. The AI's training is its experience.
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- The example -->
        <div class="section-title">üìã The Example from the Page</div>
        <div class="prompt-wrap">
            <div class="lbl">ZERO-SHOT PROMPT ‚Äî no examples provided</div>
            <pre>Classify the text into neutral, negative or positive.

Text: I think the vacation is okay.
Sentiment:</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="output-wrap">
            <div class="lbl">OUTPUT</div>
            <pre>Neutral</pre>
        </div>
        <p
            style="font-size:0.84rem; color:#94a3b8; line-height:1.65; margin-bottom:1rem;"
        >
            No examples were given. The AI wasn't shown what "neutral" looks
            like. It just understood ‚Äî because it has seen millions of sentiment
            examples during training. It already knows what sentiment
            classification is, what these three labels mean, and how to apply
            them.
        </p>

        <!-- Why it works -->
        <div class="section-title">
            üî¨ Why Does Zero-Shot Even Work? ‚Äî The "Under the Hood" Story
        </div>
        <p
            style="font-size:0.84rem; color:#94a3b8; margin-bottom:1rem; line-height:1.65;"
        >
            The page mentions two concepts ‚Äî <strong style="color:#e2e8f0;"
                >Instruction Tuning</strong
            > and <strong style="color:#e2e8f0;">RLHF</strong> ‚Äî without fully explaining
            them. Here's what they actually mean:
        </p>

        <div class="concept-row">
            <div class="concept-box it">
                <h4>üéì Instruction Tuning</h4>
                <p>
                    After initial training, the model is fine-tuned on thousands
                    of examples of <em>instructions + correct responses</em>.
                    Things like "Summarize this ‚Üí [good summary]", "Translate
                    this ‚Üí [good translation]". This teaches the model to follow
                    any instruction format, not just ones it literally saw.
                </p>
                <div class="analogy">
                    Like training an intern by giving them 10,000 varied tasks
                    with correct answers ‚Äî they learn how to handle new tasks
                    they've never seen before.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="concept-box rlhf">
                <h4>ü§ù RLHF ‚Äî Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback</h4>
                <p>
                    Human raters compare AI responses and pick which is better.
                    The AI learns to produce responses humans prefer ‚Äî more
                    helpful, more accurate, less robotic. This is what makes
                    ChatGPT, Claude, and GPT-4 feel natural to talk to, not just
                    technically correct.
                </p>
                <div class="analogy">
                    Like giving a student a grade not by comparing to a textbook
                    answer, but by asking 100 real people "which response is
                    better?" ‚Äî the student learns human preferences.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- The pipeline -->
        <div class="section-title">
            üèóÔ∏è How the AI Gets Zero-Shot Capability ‚Äî The Full Pipeline
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline">
            <div class="pipe-step">
                <div class="ps-icon">üìö</div>
                <div class="ps-title">Pre-training</div>
                <div class="ps-desc">
                    Reads billions of web pages, books, code ‚Äî learns language
                    patterns
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="pipe-arrow">‚Üí</div>
            <div class="pipe-step">
                <div class="ps-icon">üéì</div>
                <div class="ps-title">Instruction Tuning</div>
                <div class="ps-desc">
                    Fine-tuned on instruction-following datasets to understand
                    tasks
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="pipe-arrow">‚Üí</div>
            <div class="pipe-step">
                <div class="ps-icon">ü§ù</div>
                <div class="ps-title">RLHF</div>
                <div class="ps-desc">
                    Humans rank responses ‚Äî model learns what "good" actually
                    means
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="pipe-arrow">‚Üí</div>
            <div class="pipe-step" style="border-color:#6366f1;">
                <div class="ps-icon">‚ö°</div>
                <div class="ps-title">Zero-Shot Ready</div>
                <div class="ps-desc">
                    Can now handle new tasks with just an instruction ‚Äî no
                    examples needed
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- When it works vs when it fails -->
        <div class="section-title">
            ‚úÖ When Zero-Shot Works vs ‚ùå When It Fails
        </div>
        <div class="wf-grid">
            <div class="wf-card works">
                <h4>‚úÖ Zero-Shot Works Great For‚Ä¶</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        Common tasks the AI has seen millions of times
                        (sentiment, translation, summarization)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Clear, well-defined instructions with obvious expected
                        outputs
                    </li>
                    <li>General knowledge questions</li>
                    <li>Simple classification with well-known labels</li>
                    <li>
                        Writing tasks with common formats (emails, summaries,
                        titles)
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="wf-card fails">
                <h4>‚ùå Zero-Shot Struggles With‚Ä¶</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        Custom or unusual output formats (your own label names,
                        JSON schemas)
                    </li>
                    <li>Multi-step reasoning problems (math, logic puzzles)</li>
                    <li>Domain-specific tasks the AI hasn't been trained on</li>
                    <li>
                        Very strict output constraints ("respond in exactly 3
                        words")
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Nuanced tasks where "correct" is subjective or
                        context-specific
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Zero-shot vs Few-shot toggle -->
        <div class="section-title">üÜö Zero-Shot vs Few-Shot ‚Äî Side by Side</div>
        <div class="toggle-wrap">
            <h4>Click to compare the same task done both ways:</h4>
            <div class="toggle-btns">
                <div
                    class="toggle-btn active"
                    onclick="toggleMode('zero', this)"
                >
                    ‚ö° Zero-Shot
                </div>
                <div class="toggle-btn" onclick="toggleMode('few', this)">
                    üìé Few-Shot
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="toggle-content active" id="mode-zero">
                <div class="prompt-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">
                        ZERO-SHOT ‚Äî Just the instruction, no examples
                    </div>
                    <pre>Classify the text into neutral, negative or positive.

Text: I think the vacation is okay.
Sentiment:</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="output-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">OUTPUT</div>
                    <pre>Neutral  (capital N ‚Äî AI used its own format preference)</pre>
                </div>
                <p style="font-size:0.81rem; color:#94a3b8; margin-top:0.5rem;">
                    Works, but output format is unpredictable. AI decides how to
                    present the answer.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="toggle-content" id="mode-few">
                <div class="prompt-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">
                        FEW-SHOT ‚Äî Same task + 1 example to lock in format
                    </div>
                    <pre>Classify the text into neutral, negative or positive.

Text: I think the vacation is okay.
Sentiment: neutral

Text: I think the food was okay.
Sentiment:</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="output-wrap">
                    <div class="lbl">OUTPUT</div>
                    <pre>neutral  (lowercase ‚Äî copied from the example exactly)</pre>
                </div>
                <p style="font-size:0.81rem; color:#94a3b8; margin-top:0.5rem;">
                    Output format is now locked. The example teaches the AI the
                    exact style you want.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Decision tree: Should I use zero-shot? -->
        <div class="section-title">
            ü§î Should I Use Zero-Shot? ‚Äî Decision Guide
        </div>
        <div class="decision">
            <h4>Ask yourself these questions:</h4>
            <div class="d-row">
                <div class="d-q">
                    Is this a common, general task? (translation, summarization,
                    sentiment...)
                </div>
                <div class="d-arrow">‚Üí</div>
                <div class="d-a yes">
                    ‚úÖ Yes ‚Üí Try zero-shot first. It probably works.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="d-row">
                <div class="d-q">
                    Do I need the output in a very specific format or use custom
                    labels?
                </div>
                <div class="d-arrow">‚Üí</div>
                <div class="d-a no">
                    ‚ùå Yes ‚Üí Use few-shot. Add at least 1 example showing the
                    format.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="d-row">
                <div class="d-q">
                    Did zero-shot give me a wrong or messy answer?
                </div>
                <div class="d-arrow">‚Üí</div>
                <div class="d-a no">
                    ‚ùå Yes ‚Üí Switch to few-shot and add 2-3 examples.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="d-row">
                <div class="d-q">
                    Does the task require multi-step reasoning or math?
                </div>
                <div class="d-arrow">‚Üí</div>
                <div class="d-a no">
                    ‚ùå Yes ‚Üí Use Chain-of-Thought prompting (coming next).
                    Zero-shot will likely fail.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="d-row">
                <div class="d-q">
                    Is this for a quick prototype or internal tool?
                </div>
                <div class="d-arrow">‚Üí</div>
                <div class="d-a yes">
                    ‚úÖ Yes ‚Üí Zero-shot is fast, costs fewer tokens, good enough
                    to test.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tip-banner">
            <span style="font-size:1.4rem; flex-shrink:0;">üí°</span>
            <p>
                <strong>Key Takeaway:</strong> Zero-shot is your <strong
                    >first attempt</strong
                > ‚Äî fast, simple, no extra setup. If it works, great. If the output
                is wrong or oddly formatted, that's your signal to switch to few-shot
                (add examples). Think of zero-shot as "does the AI already know how
                to do this?" and few-shot as "let me show it exactly what I want."
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>

